VL  - 30
IS  - 3
SP  - 229
EP  - 247
PY  - 1991
DA  - 1991/05/01/
SN  - 0022-1996
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0022-1996(91)90020-7
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0022199691900207
AB  - In a world with high capital mobility an increase in equity taxes is likely to induce a capital out-flow. It is commonly believed that, in consequence, there may be an under-provision of public goods when governments have only equity taxes at their disposal. This paper compares the provision of public goods under cooperative and non-cooperative tax policies. Suprisingly, the non-cooperative regime may result in either an over- or an under-provision of public goods. It is also shown that the gains from coordination increase as countries become atomistic.
